    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 8,
    "last_activity_date" : 1431531125,
    "creation_date" : 1431531125,
    "answer_id" : 30219348,
    "question_id" : 5251323,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Another best way to find Java folder path is to use <code>alternatives</code> command in Fedora Linux (I know its for Ubuntu but I hit this post from google just by its headline). Just want to share incase people like me looking for answers for fedora flavour.</p>\n\n<p>To display all information regarding java</p>\n\n<pre><code>alternatives --display java\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6968593,
      "reputation" : 47,
      "user_id" : 5345700,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/524fa5d1ac3b9a9bc7e168b29903ae23?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Ashansu Pant",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5345700/ashansu-pant"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1446638289,
    "last_edit_date" : 1446638289,
    "creation_date" : 1446570411,
    "answer_id" : 33505079,
    "question_id" : 5251323,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Simple, try it:</p>\n\n<p>It's /<strong>usr/local/java/jdk[version]</strong></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5475966,
      "reputation" : 346,
      "user_id" : 4353971,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 70,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0e1d9cee8719f15795f3c56d67ecbe62?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Hasan",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4353971/hasan"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1506947517,
    "creation_date" : 1506947517,
    "answer_id" : 46525510,
    "question_id" : 5251323,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>the command: <code>sudo update-alternatives --config java</code> will find the complete path of all installed Java versions</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5996202,
      "reputation" : 560,
      "user_id" : 4710771,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/28b42d250803bea459db5210227de537?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Anubhav Gupta",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4710771/anubhav-gupta"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1522238241,
    "creation_date" : 1522238241,
    "answer_id" : 49533917,
    "question_id" : 5251323,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Three Step Process:\nFirst:\nopen Terminal-><code>$ whereis java</code>\nit would give output like this:\n<code>java: /usr/bin/java /usr/share/java /usr/share/man/man1/java.1.gz</code></p>\n\n<p>Second:\n<code>ls -l /usr/bin/java</code>\nIt would give output like this:\n<code>lrwxrwxrwx 1 root root 22 Feb  9 10:59 /usr/bin/java -&gt; /etc/alternatives/java</code></p>\n\n<p>Third:\n<code>ls -l /etc/alternatives/java</code>\noutput is the JDK path:\n<code>lrwxrwxrwx 1 root root 46 Feb  9 10:59 /etc/alternatives/java -&gt; /usr/lib/jvm/java-8-openjdk-amd64/jre/bin/java</code></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5927927,
      "reputation" : 83,
      "user_id" : 4663295,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-YFPsyC1T4ZU/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAtY/a17cnAtBkPA/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
      "display_name" : "Dread Quixadhal",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4663295/dread-quixadhal"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1549270438,
    "creation_date" : 1549270438,
    "answer_id" : 54512727,
    "question_id" : 5251323,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>This question still seems relevant, and the answer seems to be a moving target.</p>\n\n<p>On my debian system (buster):</p>\n\n<pre><code>&gt; update-java-alternatives -l\njava-1.11.0-openjdk-amd64      1111       /usr/lib/jvm/java-1.11.0-openjdk-amd64\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>However, if you actually go look there, you'll see there are multiple directories and symbolic links placed there by the package system to simplify future maintenance.</p>\n\n<p>The actual directory is <code>java-11-openjdk-amd64</code>, with another symlink of <code>default-java</code>.  There is also an <code>openjdk-11</code> directory, but it appears to only contain a source.zip file.</p>\n\n<p>Given this, for Debian ONLY, I would guess the best value to use is <code>/usr/lib/jvm/default-java</code>, as this should always be valid, even if you decide to install a totally different version of java, or even switch vendors.</p>\n\n<p>The normal reason to want to know the path is because some application wants it, and you probably don't want that app to break because you did an upgrade that changed version numbers.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5669023,
      "reputation" : 530,
      "user_id" : 4484362,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/oTjeL.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Grant Rostig",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4484362/grant-rostig"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1560046737,
    "creation_date" : 1560046737,
    "answer_id" : 56511488,
    "question_id" : 5251323,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>On Linux Fedora30 several versions of the full java JDK are available, specifically package names:</p>\n\n<pre><code>java-1.8.0-openjdk-devel.x86_64 \njava-11-openjdk-devel.x86_64\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Once installed, they are found in: <code>/usr/lib/jvm</code></p>\n\n<p>To select the location/directory of a full development JDK (which is different from the simpler runtime only JRE) look for entries:</p>\n\n<pre><code>ls -ld java*openjdk*\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Here are two good choices, which are links to specific versions, where you will have to select the version:</p>\n\n<pre><code>/usr/lib/jvm/java-1.8.0-openjdk\n/usr/lib/jvm/java-11-openjdk\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 16963741,
      "reputation" : 1,
      "user_id" : 12270227,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-BXz1bdk6r4g/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAAA/ACHi3reD3-OX0VJ4gyircYHNxZA8mp1jIA/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
      "display_name" : "Manish Sharma",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/12270227/manish-sharma"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1571938273,
    "last_edit_date" : 1571938273,
    "creation_date" : 1571938226,
    "answer_id" : 58546464,
    "question_id" : 5251323,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>This is the best way which worked for me \nExecute this Command:-</p>\n\n<pre><code>$(dirname $(readlink $(which javac)))/java_home\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1149625,
      "reputation" : 1783,
      "user_id" : 1131607,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 83,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/xLKUc.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Arun",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1131607/arun"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1605765245,
    "creation_date" : 1605765245,
    "answer_id" : 64906118,
    "question_id" : 5251323,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>below command  worked in my <code>debain 10</code> box!</p>\n<pre><code>root@debian:/home/arun# readlink -f $(which java)\n/usr/lib/jvm/java-11-openjdk-amd64/bin/java\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
